    "title": "Analytics Professional and Managing Partner",
    "topic": "Statistical Analysis of Locomotive Wheel Flange Lubrication",
    "imageSrc": "/robert-stevens.jpg",
    "bio1": "Robert Stevens is part of the leadership team at First Analytics, where he helps companies develop and execute programs to cultivate their analytics competency. His more than 30-year career in analytics has included consulting, product development, client service, technical, and sales roles within software, consulting, and market research firms.  Rob’s expertise includes applying advanced analytics techniques such as artificial intelligence, machine learning, statistical modeling, forecasting, predictive analytics, and industrial engineering.    In the rail industry, he has applied these tools to address issues such as employee and public safety, fuel conservation and reduction of greenhouse gas emissions, network operations, employee retention, locomotive reliability, and machine vision.",
    "bio2": "",
    "abstract1": "This technical presentation discusses the challenges faced by Class I railroads in North America in meeting aggressive greenhouse gas emission reduction goals set by the Science Based Targets initiative. The industry has historically improved fuel efficiency by an average of 1% per year, but to meet SBTi targets, a 6+% annual improvement is required. The paper focuses on statistical analysis tools to validate fuel savings technologies in the 1-3% range, which is challenging due to the high variability in fuel consumption and inaccurate locomotive fuel gauges. One promising technology for reducing fuel consumption and wear is locomotive wheel flange solid stick lubrication. The paper presents a case study on this technology, which involves applying a biodegradable solid lubricant to locomotive wheels.  Researchers at Kansas State University developed an environmentally friendly formulation using biopolymers and castor oil. Testing at dedicated rail facilities, such as the Transportation Technology Center (TTC) in Pueblo, Colorado, showed energy savings between 2% and 4.5% for both mechanical and electrical energy. Statistical analysis of the TTC tests, using methods like Analysis of Covariance (ANCOVA), revealed an overall fuel savings of 3.2% with a 90% confidence interval between 1.8% and 4.3%. The study also found that the lubricant reduced the outside rail gauge face coefficient of friction from 0.44 to 0.26 in a single pass. Further revenue field testing on a Class I railroad, involving over 500,000 individual crew trips, showed average savings of 1.4% to 1.8% depending on the number of locomotives equipped with lubricant brackets. The paper emphasizes the importance of rigorous statistical approaches and proper test design when evaluating fuel-saving technologies. It recommends using dedicated test facilities like TTC and MxV Rail for initial testing, followed by revenue field testing to account for variations between different railroads. ",
    "abstract2": "The authors stress the need for sufficient testing duration, diverse scenarios, and balanced experimental designs to accurately determine fuel savings and calculate return on investment. By implementing these analytical techniques, railroads can more effectively evaluate and adopt technologies that reduce fuel consumption, greenhouse gas emissions, and wheel and track wear."
