    "imageSrc": "/ralph-maldonado.jpg",
    "bio1": "Rafael (Ralph) Maldonado is Deputy Division Manager at ENSCO Rail. He has more than a decade of experience in driving key railroad technology, data analytics, and asset management solutions.  He has played a pivotal role at ENSCO in bridging the gap between data- driven insights and real-world problem solving. His expertise spans research, product development, and leadership, having held key positions such as Research Project Manager, Data Management Product Manager, and Senior Director of Digital Products and Track Inspection Services. As ENSCO’s Deputy Division Manager, he leads efforts to advance autonomous track monitoring, predictive analytics, machine vision solutions, and digital asset management platforms. Ralph specializes in leveraging technology and data to improve infrastructure reliability, operational efficiency, and safety. His work focuses on integrating automated track condition monitoring, vehicle/track interaction analytics, and development of software solutions that enable railroads to make informed, proactive decisions. He has helped railroads shift from reactive to predictive maintenance, optimizing track health and reducing risks.",
    "bio2": "Rafael holds an MS in Mechanical Engineering from the University of Texas – Pan American.",
    "abstract1": "Canadian Pacific Kansas City (CPKC) has been a pioneer in adopting autonomous and data-driven track inspection technologies, leveraging a diverse suite of systems to enhance safety, efficiency, and regulatory compliance for a combined 20,000 miles in Canada, the United States, and Mexico. With infrastructure subject to varying regulatory standards, CPKC has developed a unified approach to track inspection and maintenance that seamlessly integrates multiple advanced technologies.  CPKC employs a combination of autonomous and manned track inspection systems utilizing track geometry, rail profile, joint bar, gauge restraint measurement system, and tie assessments to name a few. This ensures continuous, real-time assessments of track conditions to detect defects before they escalate. Vehicle Track Interaction (V/TI) monitors enhance safety by identifying anomalies from in-service locomotives, particularly valuable in winter when image-based systems are limited. Machine vision systems further support inspections by capturing and analyzing high-resolution imagery to detect rail wear and tie degradation.",
    "abstract2": "Software solutions and centralized data management systems in use by CPKC ingest these diverse datasets, enabling predictive analytics and AI-driven insights to optimize maintenance, reduce disruptions, and ensure regulatory compliance.  This paper and presentation will provide an in-depth look at how these technologies are deployed across CPKC’s network, offering specific examples of how data-driven maintenance strategies have improved operational reliability."
